<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1933-06-15T20:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1933-06-15T20:00:00-05:00" n="464" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d464">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">550.S1 Monetary Stabilization/15:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to the Chairman of the American Delegation</hi>
                                (<persName type="to"><hi rend="italic">Hull</hi></persName>)</head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1933-06-15T21:00:00-04:00">June 15,
                                    1933—9 p.m.</date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>37. For Secretary of State and Cox and Sprague. The following message is
                            sent for the President. “All kinds of wild reports here about
                            stabilization at some fixed rate, some reports saying around 4 dollars
                            and other reports at other rates. I feel sure all these reports are not
                            founded in any fact. Of course any proposal must in any event come here
                            for approval or disapproval by Treasury Department and me.”</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Phillips</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>